article.description: Damon Jones, a reserve, scored all 14 of his points and Redd 11 of his 26 in the final period as the host Milwaukee Bucks rallied from a double-digit deficit to defeat the Indiana Pacers 101-96 on Friday.
article.headline: Jones, Redd the 1-2 punch for Bucks
article.linkText: Bucks win third straight, rally over Pacers
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Damon Jones says he's not a 3-point shooter. His performance against the Indiana Pacers on Friday night said otherwise. Jones scored all 14 of his points in the fourth quarter, including four 3-pointers, to help the Milwaukee Bucks climb above .500 for the first time in almost six weeks with a 101-96 victory. "I am not a 3-point specialist, but I was able to get some open looks and knock them down," said Jones, a reserve who came into the game averaging 6.8 points and shooting 39.3 percent from 3-point range. "It was a good night for me, and this was a big win for this basketball team." The victory was Milwaukee's third straight, its first such streak since winning the final four games of last season. The wins have come over three of the Eastern Conference's top teams, Indiana, New Jersey and Detroit. It was Milwaukee's second victory against the Pacers in as many tries this season. The Bucks shot over 53 percent in both games. Milwaukee moved to 15-14. Indiana dropped to 21-9 -- still the East's best record. "When you give up 34 in the fourth quarter, you deserve to be beat," Pacers coach Rick Carlisle said. "We pride ourselves on being a defensive team, and you can't let that happen." Michael Redd led the Bucks with 26 points, including a key 3-pointer with just over a minute remaining, as Milwaukee came back after trailing by as many as 15. Milwaukee outscored Indiana 34-19 in the fourth quarter. Jermaine O'Neal led the Pacers with 27 points and 11 rebounds. Ron Artest added 18, and Anthony Johnson, making his first start of the season replacing the injured Kenny Anderson, had 16. "I don't think we got the stops we should have gotten," O'Neal said. "For three quarters, we played great. It's a real disappointment to lose a game that we pretty much controlled for three quarters." Redd made a 3-pointer from the top of the key with 1:14 remaining to put Milwaukee up 99-96. Reggie Miller missed 3-pointers on Indiana's last two possessions, with Redd rebounding the second one and getting fouled with 1.8 seconds left. After blowing an early 14-0 lead, Indiana led 56-55 early in the third quarter before using a 17-4 spurt to go up 73-59. Artest had eight points during the spurt and 12 in the quarter. Jones' 3-pointer, his third of the fourth quarter, tied the game at 85 with less than seven minutes left. Another 3 by Jones from the right corner tied it at 92 with 3:41 remaining. "It was back and forth in the fourth quarter, but we were able to hit some big shots and win the game," Jones said. The Pacers held the Bucks scoreless for the game's first four minutes, but the Bucks used a 12-2 spurt to get within five after an impressive hustle play by Brian Skinner. Skinner, activated from the injured list before the game, blocked Jamaal Tinsley's baseline jumper and saved it to T.J. Ford, who found Redd for a running jumper in the lane. The Bucks tied it at 23 early in the second quarter. Skinner had 10 points in his return.

Game notes
Carlisle was critical of the officiating after the game. "My only disagreement with this game was that the fouls shouldn't have been 24-17 (in favor of the Bucks)," he said. "It's hard when your team is playing as hard as the other team and you don't get the same consideration when it comes to the whistle being blown." ... The 6-foot-9, 265-pound Skinner had missed 25 games with a knee injury. To make room on the active roster, center Joel Przybilla went on the injured list with right knee tendinitis. ... It was point guard-by-commitee for the Pacers in Anderson's absence. Tinsley scored two points in 10 minutes in his first action since being activated to replace Anderson, who went on the injured list Wednesday with a strained right calf. Tinsley left the game early in the fourth quarter after banging his head on the court.
